[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring JUnit annotations**\n\nI'm looking into how we can increase the chance of something working, maybe by adding `@Test public void getInstance(...)`? But I realize we can't do that with parameters. It seems like JUnit only registers methods that are annotated as tests. We're pretty much stuck on needing metadata for `getInstance`. Maybe I could annotate `getInstance`, but it turns out that a static method with parameters doesn't qualify as a valid test. So that's a no-go.\n\n**Considering test coverage**\n\nI think we can add a test to assert the native failure. There seems to be no known missing metadata for the negative path, which isn't supported. This could be an issue because dynamic coverage needs to ensure that both `Class#getMethod` and `Method#invoke` are reached under the native test with the current metadata. I’m wondering how we can approach this to make sure everything’s covered properly. Let's explore this further!\n\n**Evaluating JUnit Implementation**\n\nI'm considering the need for the signature `getInstance(Object)`, but it won’t function as a factory unless I use a parameterized test. JUnit is going to call it without arguments, which would cause a failure. Maybe I could annotate the helper class with `@Nested`, but that doesn't seem right either. I wonder if I could register a ParameterResolver via JUnit extension for the static `@Test`, though that might still lead to an invalid test.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0682c849c8de8b1b016a25d0e439d0819795482529951124d8\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJdEl9qxKU_qknhCqlsHIvCzVhVZpMgUAiIbzKOkn1Yh8S39AGAZgqz5MMGYQEzwZ4eqTV8nmx8GjpXhOKqmRLeUR66UiZUJlgSvITpSMw0w3zeigBVTTE3_lMa6kxjIAa_E4zEfUJHlfCYo6CeCiY2RPJsj28AoxcVnaxcHwVmlvmWPiiZMdDVqzt9gAxGIVnf4KNYTXmnsvszAp1AGy8SuBG6xorobdExTVOAu1mbhVVDZCC9HcWSY-lKuBv6EqnbmlDghO0vAAoNXXp-1OEJ-SawJnkDNuFY0mAAX